alized": true, "mention": "malformations", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9883983731269836, "span": {"begin": 668, "end": 681}}, {"id": ["mesh:D007021"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hypospadias", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999904632568359, "span": {"begin": 693, "end": 704}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "penis", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.45239126682281494, "span": {"begin": 758, "end": 763}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000728"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "androgen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995554089546204, "span": {"begin": 769, "end": 777}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10116"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "rats", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9158520102500916, "span": {"begin": 927, "end": 931}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "humans", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9847540855407715, "span": {"begin": 975, "end": 981}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013739"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "testosterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9979956150054932, "span": {"begin": 1001, "end": 1013}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013739"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "testosterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9986075758934021, "span": {"begin": 1094, "end": 1106}}, {"id": ["mesh:D007021"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hypospadias", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999842643737793, "span": {"begin": 1205, "end": 1216}}], "text": "This non-adjacent KER describes a decrease in circulating testosterone (often measured in serum or plasma) during the fetal male masculinization programming window leading to hypospadias in male offspring.   In male mammals, testosterone along with its more potent derivative dihydrotestosterone (DHT) drives male reproductive differentiation. Produced by the fetal testes, testosterone is transported through blood to the peripheral reproductive tissues to bind the androgen receptor (AR) or be converted to DHT (Murashima et al., 2015). Activation of AR in the genital tubercle directs its differentiation to a penis, and failure of this differentiation can lead to malformations, including hypospadias where the urethra terminates on the underside of the penis. The androgen programming of the genital tubercle is largely (but not fully) constrained to the masculinization programming window (gestational days (GD) 16-20 in rats, presumably gestational weeks (GW) 8-14 in humans), when circulating testosterone levels are high (Sharpe, 2020; Welsh et al., 2014).   A decrease in circulating testosterone levels in the masculinization programming window can thus disrupt penis differentiation and cause hypospadias.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:17:54 +0000 2026"}